description: From Middle English mulbery, molberye, murberie, partly from Old English mōrberġe (“mulberry”) and partly from Middle Low German mulbere (“mulberry”). Compare Dutch moerbezie, moerbei (“mulberry”), German Maulbeere (“mulberry”).

adjectives.description: mulberry (comparative more mulberry, superlative most mulberry)

entries.meaning: Of a dark purple color tinted with red.
Any of several trees, of the genus Morus, having edible fruits.
examples: Different qualities of the Mulberry. Among the different species of the Mulberry, it  is ascertained that the Italian, (Morus italica) is eaten by the silk worm, with eager  appetite. It's fruit is very small, and of a pale rose colour.

entries.meaning: A dark purple colour tinted with red.
